				<h1>Dustin K.</h1>
				<p class="about-subtitle">Astrophotographer · Deep Sky &amp; Solar Imaging</p>

				<div class="about-text">
					<p>
						By day I'm a Senior Product Support Engineer at an AI-driven SaaS
						platform — debugging email deliverability, DNS chains, CRM
						integrations, and a thousand other things across enterprise customers.
						By night and weekend, I point a camera through a telescope.
					</p>
					<p>
						I came to imaging the way I came to most things — sideways, by
						following curiosity past the boundary of what I officially know how
						to do. I've always been drawn to the night sky, but it wasn't until
						I pointed a camera through a telescope that I understood just how
						much was up there, invisible to the naked eye. A cloud of hydrogen
						gas spanning dozens of light-years. A galaxy two and a half million
						light-years away, its spiral arms resolved into individual clusters
						of stars. The idea that a sensor in my backyard could capture light
						that has been traveling since before humans existed — that still
						stops me cold.
					</p>
					<p>
						I primarily use a system built around an <strong>Orion Eon 70mm ED
						Quadruplet</strong> and a <strong>QHY 268M</strong> mono camera on
						a <strong>ZWO AM3</strong> harmonic mount. But when it's cloudy,
						as it often is here in the Pacific Northwest, I fall back to the
						<strong>iTelescope.net</strong> remote network — bigger apertures,
						darker skies, southern hemisphere access on demand.
					</p>
					<p>
						I recently acquired a <strong>Coronado Solarmax III 70mm
						double-stack</strong> hydrogen-alpha rig that I currently use
						visually. Be on the lookout for when I convert it to imaging —
						the Sun is a spectacularly dynamic target, and that pace of
						capture (sub-second lucky imaging vs. multi-hour deep sky) feels
						like a very different sport.
					</p>
					<p>
						If you're working on something cosmic — an album cover, a game
						setting, a science book — and want to talk licensing or commission,
						I'd love to hear about it.
					</p>
					<p class="about-colophon">
						I built this site too: <a href="https://www.11ty.dev" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Eleventy</a>
						for static generation, <a href="https://openseadragon.github.io" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">OpenSeadragon</a>
						for the deep-zoom viewer, <a href="https://aladin.cds.unistra.fr/AladinLite/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Aladin Lite</a>
						for the sky atlas overlays, plate-solving via
						<a href="http://nova.astrometry.net" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">astrometry.net</a> +
						<a href="https://pixinsight.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">PixInsight</a>,
						deep-zoom tile pyramids on <a href="https://www.cloudflare.com/products/r2/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Cloudflare R2</a>.
						Source on <a href="https://github.com/dustinspace217/dustin-space" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">GitHub</a>.
					</p>
					<p>
						The site name is both a pun and a description: <em>dustin.space</em>,
						because nebulae are, quite literally, dust in space. And so,
						apparently, am I.
					</p>
				</div>
